Kendrick Lamar is an American rapper, songwriter, and record producer widely regarded as one of the most influential hip-hop artists of his generation. Born on June 17, 1987, in Compton, California, Lamar gained fame for his introspective lyrics, complex storytelling, and socially conscious themes.

Lamar first garnered major attention with his 2011 album *Section.80* but achieved mainstream success with his 2012 album *good kid, m.A.A.d city*, which was praised for its vivid depiction of life in Compton. His subsequent albums, *To Pimp a Butterfly* (2015) and *DAMN.* (2017), solidified his reputation, with both receiving critical acclaim for their innovative sound and exploration of race, identity, and politics in America. *DAMN.* won the Pulitzer Prize for Music in 2018, making Lamar the first non-classical or jazz artist to receive the award.

Lamar is also known for his dynamic live performances and collaborations with other major artists. His work has earned him numerous awards, including multiple Grammy Awards, and he is often hailed as one of the greatest rappers of all time.

Despite their superficial similarities, horseshoe crabs & trilobites arenât actually super closely related. 
However, regardless of relation, they still certainly spent a lot of time alongside one another during their shared existence on Earth. 

Trilobites evolved onto the scene slightly before horseshoe crabs, but the two still shared our planet together for over 200 million years. 

Both had survived multiple mass extinctions, but unfortunately, the trilobite lineage had already been thinned dramatically by both the Devonian & Ordovician Extinctions. The final blow to the trilobites was the Permian Extinction, during which their evolutionary fortitude & luck finally ran out.

Not horseshoe crabs, though. They would go on to the survive the Permian & indeed all other mass extinction events to follow, allowing them to live all the way up to the modern day.

While horseshoe crabs may have undergone some  minor evolutionary changes, they have remained (relatively) unchanged throughout the course of their 445 million year existence on Earth.
